{
  "answer": "For Allama Iqbal, *wataniyat*—rendered in English translation as \"Nationalism\"—is a false modern idol, the greatest among the \"newer gods\" forged by contemporary civilization.[^1] It desecrates faith by draping itself in religion's garb while laying waste to the \"Prophet’s house of faith and piety,\" confining people to a single territory (which he deems a \"calamity\"), sowing rivalry among peoples, corrupting politics and trade into conquest, oppressing the weak, dividing God's creation, and severing \"the roots of Islam’s brotherhood.\"[^2][^3]\n\nIqbal counters it with a spiritual conception of homeland rooted in Islam: \"Your homeland is Islam, you serve the Prophet’s will,\" empowered by the \"strength of Oneness\" (*Tauheed*), unbound by geography—like a fish free in the ocean—and aligned with prophetic teachings where homeland exists \"by God’s command.\"[^4] This evokes the universal Islamic *ummah* (community/brotherhood) over territorial division.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Wataniyat\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-79b1e9).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Wataniyat\" [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-3b9de1:p-97937b).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Wataniyat\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-97937b).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Wataniyat\" [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-2737d5:p-a723b2).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Wataniyat\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-97937b).",
